charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
On the 10th of November, we received the difficult news that our loving dad was diagnosed with stage 3 Bowel Cancer. It was the hardest news for us all to take in and came as a shock to every one of us. Without the amazing support from Macmillan, our family would have continued to struggle to deal with this life-changing news. When we first discovered the news, we had no idea who talk to or what the next steps were. We were at a standstill. We turned to Macmillan and not only did they support our dad but the whole family. To give back to Macmillan, and other families coping with cancer, we are each doing a 30-day 30 mile run in hopes to raise as much money and awareness as we can.

Our dad didn’t show any symptoms of cancer. The way he found out was by doing a standard self-check. Along with raising money, we are hoping to raise awareness about the importance of testing for cancer.

We would appreciate donations of any value or support in sharing this post.

Thank you all!

story:
We are hoping to raise some money for Macmillan Cancer Support in honour and loving memory of Cheryl Futcher who sadly passed away on 18th December 2020. 

I think we can all agree that she was the most inspirational, strong, kindhearted lady you’d ever hope to meet. She never let her cancer diagnosis define who she was, never one to complain or dwell, she simply carried on in true Cheryl style making us so proud. 

Macmillan stepped in when our family needed them most and they will continue to support our family as long as we need them too, their work is important and so valued by so many people whose lives are affected by cancer. So if you can make a donation to this incredible charity in Cheryl’s memory, please do, Thank you xx


Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. story:
Eric was diagnosed with Mesothelioma in September 2020 which is an industrial disease related to asbestos. Prior to this, Eric enjoyed many happy years as a painter and decorator from the age of 15 before retiring in 2002 at the age of 63. 

Eric passed away peacefully in Warrington Hospital on Christmas Eve 2020 aged 81 years. The nurses on A7 cared for him with love and consideration despite the challenges they were faced with during the global pandemic of 2020. 

Macmillan cancer support were so helpful when Eric was cared for at home until he went into hospital in December 2020. Eric would be really happy that donations in his name will help other patients receive the loving care that he received.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. story: My mum faced a battle with Leukaemia 10 years ago. I am so grateful for all the time the macmillan staff spent helping us deal with the news. They organised for us to spend some quality family time together, to take our mind off of the news. They sent us on a once in a lifetime trip to the west end, to see a theatre production. My grandad has had an ongoing battle with various Cancer diagnosis, his most recent one couple of years ago. He continues the battle with the help of Macmillan. I am running 5k for 10 days to help show my appreciation for the charity.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Hi there!

I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation by attempting to run 1083 miles  - or 1,743 kilometres for metric people like me - which is the distance from Lands End to John O’Groats from January to December 2021. Of course virtually! I'd be so grateful for your support.

My dad had two heart attacks, a faulty heart valve and atric fibrillation. Without the work of researchers, insanely skilled surgical staff and mind boggling equipment and medicines he would not have lived to see five of his seven grandchildren.

My father-in-law, too, has atric fibrillation - on top of cancer. The work of these wonderful people makes it possible for him to create more memories with his grandchildren.

Your support would mean the world to me and will absolutely change lives. Plus you get updates of a chubby girl attempting running!! Thank you so much! Xx

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
We are setting up this Just Giving Page today in memory of June Tiffany. A loving Mum, Granny, Great Granny, Sister, Daughter, Auntie and Dear Friend. Her wishes were to raise funds to go to the British Heart Foundation.

Everyone who knew my mum. Would know that she had a tricky little heart. She'd had a Stent put in to save her life a number of years ago and also suffered three heart attacks in her 81 years. The third heart attack happened earlier on in the night, before she passed away peacefully in her sleep on the 24th December 2020. 

This charity is most importanty close to her heart, as a result of her dear son Michael, who also passed away from Heart Failure 5 years ago, this year. 

Thank you so, so much. Every read makes a difference in the knowledge we can spread. Every donation makes a difference in the science that can be carried out. 

Lots of love to everyone x

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page.

Brenda was a loving wife, mum, sister, granny and friend to so many. She was so kind and always went out of her way to make others happy. She was full of life and knew how to have fun. She organised the best holidays, parties, days out. 

Unfortunately over the past few years Brenda’s health deteriorated and she suffered a heart attack on the 18th of December 2020 which took her from us.

As a family we have therefore set up this link for those who would like to contribute towards the British Heart Foundation. There will be no collection at the funeral service due to Covid so this is a way for those who would like to donate to do so.

Thank you all for your kind messages and support through this heartbreaking and difficult time.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The British Heart Foundation was Dad’s charity and advances in the management of heart failure kept him with us for longer and gave us more time as a family together. Without the support of his medical team we would not have had him with us this year.

In memory of my wonderful father who has now been gone now a little over two months I’m going to walk 250,000 steps by the end of January , which will be quite tough given it’s the middle of winter!

My father was a generous man, a true gentleman and always thinking of others. I don’t think I ever heard anyone say anything but good things about him and we miss him very much. He would really have appreciated any support you can give to the Heart Foundation, even if it is just £1 so thank you for your donation.
title: Julie's fundraiser for Dad

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story: Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

charity.name: Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity
story:
This January, I'm kickstarting 2021 by taking part in Running off Christmas. I'll be running 31 miles throughout the month to raise money for Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity (GOSH Charity). After all the festivities and with the cold and wet weather January can bring, your donations to support Great Ormond Street Hospital's life saving work will keep me going when I need it most.

It's quick, easy and secure to donate, just press the Give Now button!

GOSH's patients, families and staff need your support now more than ever.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Trying to challenge myself at the moment despite there being no organised sport. definitely not a runner but chosen to run this for a great cause. 

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

OUR STORY💛

Helz, Anna, Suz, Bex, Mandy and Sarah have joined together to create a walking tribe to raise money for The Heidi Taylor Brighter Future Fund, with all proceeds going to Great Ormond Street Hospital Children’s Charity. We’ve named our tribe ‘Sole Sistas’, and each of us plan to walk the distance of Lands End to John O’Groats during 2021, a whopping 1083.8 miles!!!

Heidi, Anna’s sister In law, was only 33 when she was taken from this world. She was taken ill on Christmas Eve 2014 and was subsequently diagnosed with a Grade 4 Brain Tumour. After a brave and courageous battle she sadly passed away on the 4th November 2015.

Heidi was a Paediatric Nurse, and a true credit to the profession. To continue her beautiful legacy and create a brighter future for children, we will walk every step in her memory.

Many of our tribe know first hand the help Heidis fund and GOSH children’s charity provides to our younger generations. Ella, Helz and Suz’s wonderful niece lives with only half a heart. GOSH saved Ella’s life, rebuilding her heart and keeping her safe for many years! The vital research provided by this charity ensures children like Ella survive the challenges they have been dealt.

So, we walk for Heidi and Ella!!! Heidis legacy and Ella’s continued strength will carry us all the way.

If you would like to contribute to the fund please follow the link below. Every little counts.

Thank you 

Sole Sistas

story: This January, I'm kickstarting 2021 by taking part in Running off Christmas. I'll be running 31 miles throughout the month to raise money for Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity (GOSH Charity). My niece, Hollie, was rushed to GOSH as a baby after her condition critically deteriorated following heart surgery. Thanks to the amazing skills of the team at GOSH Hollie made a full recovery and is now in her twenties. I haven't been running for long but I'm putting my rookie running skills to the test to raise funds to say thank you to GOSH for all the amazing work they do. The hospital relies on charitable support to go above and beyond, to provide the extraordinary care, expertise and facilities that give seriously ill children from across the UK the best chance to fulfil their potential. Please join me in saying thank you, your donations to support Great Ormond Street Hospital's life saving work will keep me going when I need it most. It's quick, easy and secure to donate, just press the Give Now button! GOSH's patients, families and staff need your support now more than ever.

We are the world’s largest charity dedicated to saving lives through research.
Our vision is to bring forward the day when all cancers are cured.

Cancer Research UK is a registered charity in England and Wales (1089464), Scotland (SC041666), the Isle of Man (1103) and Jersey (247).
charity.name: Cancer Research UK
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 1089464, Scotland SC041666
eventName: Clock up 65KM in January for Cancer Research UK
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Covid-19 has impacted fundraising in 2021. I am not a fast runner, more of a plodder really, but I thought I would lace up my trainers and strive to clock up 65km in January to try to raise funds for cancer research. 

There are so many worthy charities but I chose Cancer Research as it covers all cancers.  Sadly, cancer has impacted everybody I know in some way and as we know research is crucial in the battle against cancer.

January is a tough month financially for most people, probably more so this year with the impact of Covid, but if you can spare a few pounds it will be greatly appreciated.  It will also spur me on when opening the door to go out in the rain, wind and probable snow that January offers!

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

eventName: Lands end to John o groats
story:
Thank you for visiting my just giving page. 

Last year I was diagnosed with skin cancer. It was a shock not only to myself but my family as a whole. I was helped and supported by many friends and family. I would like to show my appreciation by raising money for cancer research uk. 

One way or another over your lifetime you will know someone or be affected yourself by a form of cancer. 

I will be covering the distance from lands end to John o groats (874miles).  I will be doing this by running and cycling the distance. I will be trying to complete this by cycling to and from my work place, also by running as much as I can. 

The time frame I have set to do this is a year. I hope to easily do the challenge within the time frame. If I do then I will keep on going raising what I can for a worthwhile cause.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page. 3 years ago I raised over £800 for this amazing charity  with my “50 bakes for cancer research” thanks to all the very  generous people who contributed. 

 In 2020 and for the foreseeable future  charity bake sales which I regularly arrange at work to raise money will not be possible. 

So it is a virtual bake sale again.  My “50 bakes”  was  to mark my 50th birthday( and because a family member was receiving treatment for cancer).  53  (which is my age on my next birthday in March) is  not an interesting  number so I have chosen 60 instead.  So, over 2021 I’ll try new things and challenge myself!

Help me smash my last total and get £1000 for this charity! I’ll post photos of the bakes as I go and update totals etc

story:
Hi! Thanks for checking out my Just Giving Page!

Sophie and I are running Bath Half this year to raise money for Cancer Research UK. It’ll be a huge challenge for both of us and for a fantastic cause. We all know at least one person who had been affected by Cancer and your donations will be put to good use, helping to find more effective ways to treat and cure this evil disease.

My Grandad Trevor passed away from a Brain Tumour several years ago now, and I chose Cancer Research as I’ve wanted to fundraise for them for a while in memory of him. Having lost my Grandad Rob this last year, it’ll also be a fitting tribute to him (you might remember I did Bournemouth Half in 2018 for Parkinsons UK).

Think of those you know who have been affected by Cancer and throw a few quid in the pot if you can. Your generosity is really appreciated and I’m grateful for your support!

Lots of love,

Byron <3

PS - be sure to donate to Sophie’s page as well (we have to have separate fundraising pages to hit our individual fundraising targets!)

Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

  • Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

If you that know me will know that this charity is so important to me. In 1996, Cancer took the life, not only of my husband, but my boys Dad; Jake, aged just 26 years.

 
Jake's death had an unforgettable impact to our family and friends. Over the 3 years after diagnosis, he had various treatments including chemotherapy, radiotherapy and a stem-cell transplant. Cancer Research was such an important part of this journey not only medically but they gave us financial and emotional support.
 
I would like to give something back to them, albeit it's just a half marathon walk.

Cancer seems to continue affecting the lives of people that I care very much about. I am not only doing this walk in the memory of my boys Dad, but also for my partner Martin's step dad, John and his step brother Jim as well as old school friends that have all left us way to soon.

story:
773.9 km, 105 days, 2 feet, £2,000 target, and a lot of will power!

I’ve decided to take on a new challenge at the start of 2021. Partly to give a focus during the on-going uncertainty, but also to do my small part for others, and to keep myself fit and healthy.

Over the next 105 days I am going to be virtually walking the Camino de Santiago.  This will involve walking on average 4 miles a day (6.4km). I will be doing this alongside working from home and trying to achieve some other challenges I’ve set myself for the year. And I will be doing the walk whilst we are still restricted, and during the coldest, wettest, and sometimes darkest days of the year…... So, I think it will be a challenge!

As I do this virtual pilgrimage, I am raising money for two
charities (you can choose the charity you would like your money to go to - there are two links): Cancer Research UK and Tearfund.  I have family and friends who work in medical research and I know the importance of it especially for finding cures and medical breakthroughs for cancers and other diseases. I also have family and friends who have been affected by cancer and I know that the work of Cancer Research UK is so critical to help others living with and recovering from cancer.

Many of you know that I work for Tearfund, a Christian charity which partners with churches in more than 50 of the world’s poorest
countries. We tackle poverty and injustice through sustainable development, by responding to disasters and challenging injustice. We believe an end to extreme poverty is possible.

I am also happy to have walking companions (you don’t need to raise any money). If you would like to join me on the Camino, do let me know and I can share the app I am using (there is a small fee to pay – it is not linked to either charity). It tracks your progress and gives you updates and photos of the places you are walking through.  We can walk together!  And you will also be planting 5 trees as part of using the app. 

It would be wonderful if you would like to support me in this challenge. I will share updates over the coming weeks.

My challenge starts on Sunday 3rd January 2021.

Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

story:
As you probably all know, I really don't like having long hair and so growing it out has been a big challenge for me.  Whenever I hear about someone I know being diagnosed with cancer, my heart breaks and I would like to do everything that I can to help them.  Cancer is a horrible disease, causing suffering and heartache for lots of people and I hope that one day we can put a stop to it.

On top of shaving my head, I will be donating my hair to the Little Princess Trust so that they can make it into a lovely wig for a child who is having treatment and have lost their hair.  I hope that my hair will put a smile on their face and that the money will help fund research,  

If you donate, you could also help to change lives and potentially save lives too.  Thank you so much for supporting me!  Watch out for updates and a video of the big shave just as soon as possible!  I am a bit nervous but determined to do this.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

As we all know we lost a great friend Toby Dawson in may this year after a courageous and spirited fight against cancer. 

During tobys fight the football community and many others came together to raise an amazing amount to help support Toby, Kelly and there little family financially through a very difficult period. 

After Toby sadly passed away myself and a few others had so many plans in place to raise money for cancer research uk in Tobys memory but unfortunately the coronavirus put an end to any of these plans. 

However I’ve decided to try and get the ball rolling, I’m aiming to run 200km in January and for anyone who knows me running isn’t my greatest attribute and yes it will be hard and it will hurt but nothing can compare to what Toby went through so I’m going to push my limits and do this for Toby and hopefully raise a few quid for such a deserving charity. 

I know times are hard for many of us but if you can find a spare few quid I’d be so grateful and I know Toby's family will be so happy knowing that yet again we’ve  all come together but this time we are supporting a great charity that not only helped Toby and his family during there darkest hours but will also continue to help many others. 

Thanks for your support

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Duncan, myself and family would like to thank everybody for their kind messages of support with the loss of Lorna, our earth angel. We have had so many people wishing to donate to a charity in memory of Lorna, which has touched all of our hearts. Due to Covid restrictions this was going to prove difficult. So we have set up this Just Giving page where any donation will go straight to the charity. 

The charity the family have chose is Cancer Research UK. Lorna has battled cancer for a number of years with grace, dignity and strength. Lorna would have done anything to find a cure, not only to help herself but the many people she knew also fighting. 

Thank you from the bottom of our heart for any donations made.

Our world has been rocked with the shocking  diagnosis of stage 3 lung cancer in my husband and we received this news just before Christmas.  It’s such a cruel world and we are devastated.  As there is nothing that I can do to make him better I will be right beside him every step of the way and I want to make every step count by raising funds for cancer research. 

Cancer touches just about everyone now and this is not for the first time in our family with both my mum and brother being survivors but sadly this disease took both my mother-in-law and father-in-law over the past few years.  

I hope and pray that a cure can be found for this vile disease. Thanks for supporting us 🙏❤️

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

charity.name: Marie Curie
story: We have all been best friends for around 11 years now, meeting whilst serving in the British Military. Some of us have changed career, we are all living in different parts of the UK and our friendships have struggled at times but we are still now and always will be connected with love, mutual appreciation and fond memories. We don't get to see eachother as often as we would like but we are coming together now to try and raise as much money as possible for an amazing, worthy cause. Last year Ellie's step-dad (Joe) whom we have set up this page in memory of, died from cancer. Joe was diagnosed very abruptly and once they knew that he had cancer the disease quickly took over and Joe did not get very long to live. It was extremely hard for the family especially with the type of year it was in 2020 (Covid-19) but Marie Curie were there to help them through their darkest days. L Last month Ellie managed to raise an amazing £800 for the charity and so we have decided to join her in her quest to raise even more money in Joe's memory. Any money that you can give would be amazing and we will all appreciate it so much! We all have different running abilities and experience but hope that together we can reach our target of 200 miles. It will be tough but with your donations to keep us motivated and our supportive friendships we are hoping we can pull this off. Thank you to everyone who takes the time to visit our page and donate.

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page.

Our dad was diagnosed with terminal cancer and died less that two weeks later under horrifying circumstances.  Cancer robbed our dad of his chance to watch his grandchildren grow and ripped the heart out of our family.  Tragically, so many of us have first hand experience of how this cruel, horrifying disease can take away the ones you love and make you feel so helpless.  It has changed us in ways we could not have ever imagined and left us traumatised and heartbroken.

There are no words that we can find to describe the kindness, care and support each and everyone a Marie Curie gave our dad. The love they showed goes way beyond any job role.  Marie Curie nurses are like no other and treat everyone with such dignity, compassion and with the respect they deserve towards the end of their lives.  

We want to do something incredible for people living with a terminal illness.  We have decided to challenge ourselves by plunging into an ice bath everyday at 5am for 5 minutes, for 30 days.  

Our aim is to raise as much money as possible for this phenomenal cause.  Marie Curie needs your help to continue this incredible support to provide care for those who need it.  

Whether it is 5p or £5 it all makes a massive difference. 

Please help us raise money to help nurses provide vital care to people with terminal illness and their loved ones.  


Amanda & Martine xx

charity.name: Marie Curie
story: My Grandad spent a week at the Marie Curie Hospice at Woolton in Liverpool. Everyone who provided care for him at home at at the hospice were amazing. He was looked after by a nurse in his fifties, who used to be in the merchant navy and he shaved my Grandad every day and made sure he had his watch on. He understood what my Grandad wanted to preserve his dignity in his final days. The staff also looked after and my Gran amazingly as she went through this with him. They supported us through our most difficult time and this is our small way of saying thank you.

charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

story:
2021 is the year of my 50th birthday. I wanted to set myself a challenge to get fit and lose weight after letting myself go in lockdown.(and we’ll before). I thought I’d set myself a challenging  target and at the same time try and raise money for a charity close to my heart. Sadly, I have had too much experience of their wonderful work over the years. By doing this I hope to be able to raise some much needed funds to help them continue providing invaluable support to people in the most awful of circumstances.

My birthday is on 10th May so that gives me just over 4 months to lose 50lbs. I’ll keep you updated on my progress.

charity.description:
We’re the world’s leading independent conservation organisation. And we’re building a future where people and nature thrive together. 

That’s why we’re passionate about sharing the planet’s resources more sustainably, tackling climate change and protecting endangered wildlife.
charity.name: WWF-UK
story:
I am going to run 5 miles in one day to raise money to help endangered animals and the World Wildlife Foundation. I love animals so much and when I am older I want to be a vet. I want to do all that I can to help the most vulnerable animals on our planet and to play my part in conservation. 

On Sunday 10th January I am going to run one mile per hour. With the remaining time in each hour I am going to complete a total of five activities to help the conservation of our wildlife. 

My first activity is to go litter picking and to recycle as much as possible from the litter that I collect. My second activity is to cook a planet-friendly sustainable recipe for my lunch. My third activity is to complete an upcycling project. My fourth activity is to sign up to become an ocean hero and help to reduce plastic waste. The final activity is to plant native plants into my garden to provide native food for the pollinators.

During home-school this month, my sister and I are also going to be studying the critically endangered Bornean Orangutan and the endangered Galapagos Penguin. One day, we hope to travel to Borneo and to the Galapagos islands to see these animals for real and to spread our love. At the end of our project we will be 'adopting' one of each of these animals.

I hope to raise £100 to go direct to the WWF to support their amazing work. I would be so grateful for your support. I LOVE ANIMALS. 

love Elodie x

Thats because half of all UK species are in decline were losing our precious red squirrels, hedgehogs and birds at an alarming rate. By taking part in The Big Winter Wander, you and your friends and family can reconnect with our country's beautiful wildlife and help protect it. The funds you raise will help us campaign to protect wildlife here, and around the world. Nature has been there to offer us comfort during difficult times, and now its our time to give back.

charity.name: WWF-UK
story:
January can feel like a lifeless and uneventful month after the winter festivities have ended and the British landscape can feel like that too (unless we ate lucky enough to get a flurry of snow!). T

hat is why RootEd has decided take part in the WWF's Big Winter Wander, to help lift your spirits, as well as raising funds to help the WWF continue their vital work fighting for wildlife everywhere. 

WWF is at the heart of global efforts to address the world’s most important environmental challenges: safeguarding the natural world, tackling climate change and enabling people to use only their fair share of natural resources. Together we can build a future where people and nature thrive.Your support is much appreciated.Find out more by visiting wwf.org.uk

Join us on 1 of 3 winter wanders in mystery locations around South Yorkshire, reconnecting with our region's beautiful winter wildlife and helping to protect it, too.

Around 100 Amur leopards remain in the wild and their habitat is under threat from logging, forest fires and road and industrial development.

Zac is going to cover 100 miles in January... 1 mile for every Amur Leopard. He will do this by cycling, walking, running (and swimming if possible).

He would love it if you could sponsor him

We’re the world’s leading independent conservation organisation. And we’re building a future where people and nature thrive together. 

That’s why we’re passionate about sharing the planet’s resources more sustainably, tackling climate change and protecting endangered wildlife.
charity.name: WWF-UK
story: IF YOU GO DOWN TO THE WOODS TODAY... You might notice theres less wildlife than there used to be. Thats because half of all UK species are in decline were losing our precious red squirrels, hedgehogs and birds at an alarming rate. By taking part in The Big Winter Wander, you and your friends and family can reconnect with our country's beautiful wildlife and help protect it. The funds you raise will help us campaign to protect wildlife here, and around the world. Nature has been there to offer us comfort during difficult times, and now its our time to give back.

story:
The challenge is to complete all the components of an Ironman in 2020. It will not be all on same day, probably not even the same month :) as this consists of a 2.4 mile swim, a 112 mile bike ride, and just a little 26.2 mile marathon to top it off.

Never done any of these before and no doubt lockdown will be an added challenge, but that is the plan.

Massively appreciate all your support and it’s for a really great cause...

WWF is at the heart of global efforts to address the world’s most important environmental challenges: safeguarding the natural world, tackling climate change and enabling people to use only their fair share of natural resources. Together we can build a future where people and nature thrive. Find out more by visiting wwf.org.uk

charity.description: Oxfam is a global movement of people who won’t live with the injustice of poverty. Together we save lives in disasters. We help people build better lives for themselves. We speak out on the big issues, like inequality and climate change. And we won’t stop until we end poverty for everyone. Join us
charity.name: Oxfam
story:
Climate change is affecting millions of the worlds poorest people, right now. More frequent and extreme weather is destroying homes, and wrecking lives. The people who have done the least to cause the climate emergency are being hit the hardest this is an injustice that can and must be stopped.

Oxfam is protecting families forced to flee their homes, supporting those hit by changing weather, making sure children have a chance of a future free from poverty and responding to the deadly threat of coronavirus. Through all of this, we rely on brilliant supporters like you to make sure our dedicated teams can be where they're needed most. We couldn't do our work without you.

Every donation, no matter how big or small, makes a difference. 

Together, we won't live with poverty.

charity.description: Right now, millions of children are in danger. They face violence, disease, hunger and the chaos of war and disaster. Unicef ensures more children get life-saving food, vaccinations, education and protection than anyone else. With your help, we can build a safer world for children. unicef.org.uk
charity.name: Unicef UK
story: Throughout the globe Covid-19 has spread rapidly. Although UK has seen its own share of illness and death we are very lucky enough to have first class healthcare service and government support in this crisis. Unfortunately others around the world are not so lucky. In an attempt to give back to those in need this February Isaac Guppy, Cam Graetz, Max Waldron and Julian Hannah have set themselves a challenge to run 300km each throughout the month (averaging 10km a day) in order to raise money for UNICEF. UNICEF, also known as the united nations children’s fund, is a United Nations agency responsible for providing humanitarian and developmental aid to children worldwide. We extend the invitation to anyone who would like to join us on our ‘Rona Run’ or set your own challenge for the month and help support those in need!

charity.name: Medecins Sans Frontieres / Doctors Without Borders (MSF)
story:

charity.name: Medecins Sans Frontieres / Doctors Without Borders (MSF)
story:
I'm challenging myself to run four times my usual weekly distance for four weeks in January.  I'm hoping to raise some money for Doctors Without Borders (MSF) while doing this.  I know that because of the coronavirus pandemic medical services around the world are going to be incredibly stretched in the year ahead. Doctors Without Borders aim to take medical care to where it's needed most.

Please sponsor me here if this is a cause you would like to support and it's affordable for you to do so at the moment. Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.  

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
story: I am challenging myself to drink nothing but water this January. I am taking on the ultimate detox by avoiding caffeine, alcohol and all other drinks while supporting WaterAid. Give before 4 February 2021 and your donation will be doubled by the UK government, up to £2 million, making double the difference in communities across Ethiopia. Together, we will bring clean water to 50,000 people in Ethiopia and thousands more around the world, helping them change their own lives, forever. If you would like further information about the difference your gift will make and the positive impact it will have on peoples lives, please visit us at www.wateraid.org/uk
